/Core/namespace.name: namespace
/Core/namespace.summary:
Provides an unambiguous mechanism for conveying a URI fragment portion of an
Element ID.
/Core/namespace.description:
A namespace provides an unambiguous mechanism for conveying a URI fragment
portion of an Element ID.

/Core/locator.name: locator
/Core/locator.summary: Provides the location of an external reference.
/Core/locator.description: A locator provides the location of an external reference.

/Core/extension.name: extension
/Core/extension.summary: Specifies an Extension characterization of some aspect of an Element.
/Core/extension.description:
`extension` specifies an Extension-based characterization of a particular
aspect of an Element.

/Core/profileConformance.name: profileConformance
/Core/profileConformance.summary:
Describes one a profile which the creator of this ElementCollection intends to
conform to.
/Core/profileConformance.description:
Describes a profile to which the creator of this ElementCollection intends to
conform.

The profileConformance will apply to all Elements contained within the
collection as well as the collection itself.

Conformance to a profile is defined by the additional restrictions documented
in the profile specific documentation and schema files.

Use of this property allows the creator of an ElementCollection to communicate
to consumers their intent to adhere to the profile additional restrictions.

The profileConformance has a default value of core if no other
profileConformance is specified since all ElementCollections and Element must
adhere to the core profile.

/Core/beginIntegerRange.name: beginIntegerRange
/Core/beginIntegerRange.summary: Defines the beginning of a range.
/Core/beginIntegerRange.description: beginIntegerRange is a positive integer that defines the beginning of a range.

/Core/supportLevel.name: supportLevel
/Core/supportLevel.summary: Specifies the level of support associated with an artifact.
/Core/supportLevel.description:
supportLevel provides an indication of what support expectations that the
supplier of an artifact is providing to the user.

/Core/summary.name: summary
/Core/summary.summary: A short description of an Element.
/Core/summary.description:
A summary is a short description of an Element. Here, the intent is to allow
the Element creator to provide concise information about the function or use of
the Element.

/Core/builtTime.name: builtTime
/Core/builtTime.summary: Specifies the time an artifact was built.
/Core/builtTime.description: A builtTime specifies the time an artifact was built.

/Core/createdBy.name: createdBy
/Core/createdBy.summary: Identifies who or what created the Element.
/Core/createdBy.description:
CreatedBy identifies who or what created the Element.

The generation method will assist the recipient of the Element in assessing
the general reliability/accuracy of the analysis information.

/Core/creationInfo.name: creationInfo
/Core/creationInfo.summary: Provides information about the creation of the Element.
/Core/creationInfo.description: CreationInfo provides information about the creation of the Element.

/Core/contentType.name: contentType
/Core/contentType.summary: Provides information about the content type of an Element or a Property.
/Core/contentType.description:
This field is a reasonable estimation of the content type of the Element or the
Property, from a creator perspective.

Content type is intrinsic to the Element or the Property, independent of how it
is being used.

/Core/PresenceType.name: PresenceType
/Core/PresenceType.description: This type is used to indicate if a given field is present or absent or unknown.

entries.noAssertion: Makes no assertion about the field.

/Core/RelationshipType.name: RelationshipType
/Core/RelationshipType.summary: Information about the relationship between two Elements.
/Core/RelationshipType.description:
Provides information about the relationship between two Elements.
For example, you can represent a relationship between two different Files,
between a Package and a File, between two Packages, or between one SpdxDocument
and another SpdxDocument.

Relationship names should be descriptive enough to easily deduce the correct direction
from their name. The best way to do this is to make sure that the relationship
name completes the sentence:

`from` (is) (a) `RELATIONSHIP` `to`

entries.affects: The `from` Vulnerability affects each `to` Element. The use of the `affects` type is constrained to `VexAffectedVulnAssessmentRelationship` classed relationships.
entries.amendedBy: The `from` Element is amended by each `to` Element.
entries.ancestorOf: The `from` Element is an ancestor of each `to` Element.
entries.availableFrom: The `from` Element is available from the additional supplier described by each `to` Element.
entries.configures: The `from` Element is a configuration applied to each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.coordinatedBy: The `from` Vulnerability is coordinatedBy the `to` Agent(s) (vendor, researcher, or consumer agent).
entries.copiedTo: The `from` Element has been copied to each `to` Element.
entries.delegatedTo: The `from` Agent is delegating an action to the Agent of the `to` Relationship (which must be of type invokedBy), during a LifecycleScopeType (e.g. the `to` invokedBy Relationship is being done on behalf of `from`).
entries.dependsOn: The `from` Element depends on each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.descendantOf: The `from` Element is a descendant of each `to` Element.
entries.describes: The `from` Element describes each `to` Element. To denote the root(s) of a tree of elements in a collection, the rootElement property should be used.
entries.doesNotAffect: The `from` Vulnerability has no impact on each `to` Element. The use of the `doesNotAffect` is constrained to `VexNotAffectedVulnAssessmentRelationship` classed relationships.
entries.expandsTo: The `from` archive expands out as an artifact described by each `to` Element.
entries.exploitCreatedBy: The `from` Vulnerability has had an exploit created against it by each `to` Agent.
entries.fixedBy: Designates a `from` Vulnerability has been fixed by the `to` Agent(s).
entries.fixedIn: A `from` Vulnerability has been fixed in each `to` Element. The use of the `fixedIn` type is constrained to `VexFixedVulnAssessmentRelationship` classed relationships.
entries.foundBy: Designates a `from` Vulnerability was originally discovered by the `to` Agent(s).
entries.hasAddedFile: Every `to` Element is a file added to the `from` Element (`from` hasAddedFile `to`).
entries.hasAssessmentFor: Relates a `from` Vulnerability and each `to` Element with a security assessment. To be used with `VulnAssessmentRelationship` types.
entries.hasAssociatedVulnerability: Used to associate a `from` Artifact with each `to` Vulnerability.
entries.hasConcludedLicense: The `from` SoftwareArtifact is concluded by the SPDX data creator to be governed by each `to` license.
entries.hasDataFile: The `from` Element treats each `to` Element as a data file. A data file is an artifact that stores data required or optional for the `from` Element's functionality. A data file can be a database file, an index file, a log file, an AI model file, a calibration data file, a temporary file, a backup file, and more. For AI training dataset, test dataset, test artifact, configuration data, build input data, and build output data, please consider using the more specific relationship types: `trainedOn`, `testedOn`, `hasTest`, `configures`, `hasInput`, and `hasOutput`, respectively. This relationship does not imply dependency.
entries.hasDeclaredLicense: The `from` SoftwareArtifact was discovered to actually contain each `to` license, for example as detected by use of automated tooling.
entries.hasDeletedFile: Every `to` Element is a file deleted from the `from` Element (`from` hasDeletedFile `to`).
entries.hasDependencyManifest: The `from` Element has manifest files that contain dependency information in each `to` Element.
entries.hasDistributionArtifact: The `from` Element is distributed as an artifact in each `to` Element (e.g. an RPM or archive file).
entries.hasDocumentation: The `from` Element is documented by each `to` Element.
entries.hasDynamicLink: The `from` Element dynamically links in each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasEvidence: Every `to` Element is considered as evidence for the `from` Element (`from` hasEvidence `to`).
entries.hasExample: Every `to` Element is an example for the `from` Element (`from` hasExample `to`).
entries.hasHost: The `from` Build was run on the `to` Element during a LifecycleScopeType period (e.g. the host that the build runs on).
entries.hasInput: The `from` Build has each `to` Element as an input, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasMetadata: Every `to` Element is metadata about the `from` Element (`from` hasMetadata `to`).
entries.hasOptionalComponent: Every `to` Element is an optional component of the `from` Element (`from` hasOptionalComponent `to`).
entries.hasOptionalDependency: The `from` Element optionally depends on each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasOutput: The `from` Build element generates each `to` Element as an output, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasPrerequisite: The `from` Element has a prerequisite on each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasProvidedDependency: The `from` Element has a dependency on each `to` Element, dependency is not in the distributed artifact, but assumed to be provided, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasRequirement: The `from` Element has a requirement on each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasSpecification: Every `to` Element is a specification for the `from` Element (`from` hasSpecification `to`), during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasStaticLink: The `from` Element statically links in each `to` Element, during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasTest: Every `to` Element is a test artifact for the `from` Element (`from` hasTest `to`), during a LifecycleScopeType period.
entries.hasTestCase: Every `to` Element is a test case for the `from` Element (`from` hasTestCase `to`).
entries.hasVariant: Every `to` Element is a variant the `from` Element (`from` hasVariant `to`).
entries.invokedBy: The `from` Element was invoked by the `to` Agent, during a LifecycleScopeType period (for example, a Build element that describes a build step).
entries.modifiedBy: The `from` Element is modified by each `to` Element.
entries.other: Every `to` Element is related to the `from` Element where the relationship type is not described by any of the SPDX relationhip types (this relationship is directionless).
entries.packagedBy: Every `to` Element is a packaged instance of the `from` Element (`from` packagedBy `to`).
entries.patchedBy: Every `to` Element is a patch for the `from` Element (`from` patchedBy `to`).
entries.publishedBy: Designates a `from` Vulnerability was made available for public use or reference by each `to` Agent.
entries.reportedBy: Designates a `from` Vulnerability was first reported to a project, vendor, or tracking database for formal identification by each `to` Agent.
entries.republishedBy: Designates a `from` Vulnerability's details were tracked, aggregated, and/or enriched to improve context (i.e. NVD) by each `to` Agent.
entries.serializedInArtifact: The `from` SpdxDocument can be found in a serialized form in each `to` Artifact.
entries.testedOn: The `from` Element has been tested on the `to` Element(s).
entries.trainedOn: The `from` Element has been trained on the `to` Element(s).
entries.underInvestigationFor: The `from` Vulnerability impact is being investigated for each `to` Element. The use of the `underInvestigationFor` type is constrained to `VexUnderInvestigationVulnAssessmentRelationship` classed relationships.
entries.usesTool: The `from` Element uses each `to` Element as a tool, during a LifecycleScopeType period.

/Core/ProfileIdentifierType.name: ProfileIdentifierType
/Core/ProfileIdentifierType.description:
There are a set of profiles that have been defined by a profile team.

A profile consists of a namespace that may add properties and classes to the
core profile unique to the domain covered by the profile.

The profile may also contain additional restrictions on existing properties and
classes defined in other profiles.

If the creator of an SPDX collection of elements includes a profile in the list
of profileConformance, they are claiming that all contained elements conform
to all restrictions defined for that profile.

entries.core: the element follows the Core profile specification
entries.software: the element follows the Software profile specification
entries.simpleLicensing: the element follows the simple Licensing profile specification
entries.expandedLicensing: the element follows the expanded Licensing profile specification
entries.security: the element follows the Security profile specification
entries.build: the element follows the Build profile specification
entries.ai: the element follows the AI profile specification
entries.dataset: the element follows the Dataset profile specification
entries.extension: the element follows the Extension profile specification
entries.lite: the element follows the Lite profile specification

/Core/ExternalRefType.name: ExternalRefType
/Core/ExternalRefType.summary: Specifies the type of an external reference.
/Core/ExternalRefType.description: ExternalRefType specifies the type of an external reference.

entries.altDownloadLocation: A reference to an alternative download location.
entries.altWebPage: A reference to an alternative web page.
entries.binaryArtifact: A reference to binary artifacts related to a package.
entries.bower: A reference to a Bower package. The package locator format, looks like `package#version`, is defined in the "install" section of [Bower API documentation](https://bower.io/docs/api/#install).
entries.buildMeta: A reference build metadata related to a published package.
entries.buildSystem: A reference build system used to create or publish the package.
entries.chat: A reference to the instant messaging system used by the maintainer for a package.
entries.certificationReport: A reference to a certification report for a package from an accredited/independent body.
entries.componentAnalysisReport: A reference to a Software Composition Analysis (SCA) report.
entries.cwe: [Common Weakness Enumeration](https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/common_weakness_enumeration). A reference to a source of software flaw defined within the official [CWE List](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/) that conforms to the [CWE specification](https://cwe.mitre.org/).
entries.documentation: A reference to the documentation for a package.
entries.dynamicAnalysisReport: A reference to a dynamic analysis report for a package.
entries.eolNotice: A reference to the End Of Sale (EOS) and/or End Of Life (EOL) information related to a package.
entries.exportControlAssessment: A reference to a export control assessment for a package.
entries.funding: A reference to funding information related to a package.
entries.issueTracker: A reference to the issue tracker for a package.
entries.mailingList: A reference to the mailing list used by the maintainer for a package.
entries.mavenCentral: A reference to a Maven repository artifact. The artifact locator format is defined in the [Maven documentation](https://maven.apache.org/guides/mini/guide-naming-conventions.html) and looks like `groupId:artifactId[:version]`.
entries.metrics: A reference to metrics related to package such as OpenSSF scorecards.
entries.npm: A reference to an npm package. The package locator format is defined in the [npm documentation](https://docs.npmjs.com/cli/v10/configuring-npm/package-json) and looks like `package@version`.
entries.nuget: A reference to a NuGet package. The package locator format is defined in the [NuGet documentation](https://docs.nuget.org) and looks like `package/version`.
entries.license: A reference to additional license information related to an artifact.
entries.other: Used when the type does not match any of the other options.
entries.privacyAssessment: A reference to a privacy assessment for a package.
entries.productMetadata: A reference to additional product metadata such as reference within organization's product catalog.
entries.purchaseOrder: A reference to a purchase order for a package.
entries.qualityAssessmentReport: A reference to a quality assessment for a package.
entries.releaseNotes: A reference to the release notes for a package.
entries.releaseHistory: A reference to a published list of releases for a package.
entries.riskAssessment: A reference to a risk assessment for a package.
entries.runtimeAnalysisReport: A reference to a runtime analysis report for a package.
entries.secureSoftwareAttestation: A reference to information assuring that the software is developed using security practices as defined by [NIST SP 800-218 Secure Software Development Framework (SSDF) Version 1.1](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/218/final) or [CISA Secure Software Development Attestation Form](https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/resources/secure-software-development-attestation-form).
entries.securityAdvisory: A reference to a published security advisory (where advisory as defined per [ISO 29147:2018](https://www.iso.org/standard/72311.html)) that may affect one or more elements, e.g., vendor advisories or specific NVD entries.
entries.securityAdversaryModel: A reference to the security adversary model for a package.
entries.securityFix: A reference to the patch or source code that fixes a vulnerability.
entries.securityOther: A reference to related security information of unspecified type.
entries.securityPenTestReport: A reference to a [penetration test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penetration_test) report for a package.
entries.securityPolicy: A reference to instructions for reporting newly discovered security vulnerabilities for a package.
entries.securityThreatModel: A reference the [security threat model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Threat_model) for a package.
entries.socialMedia: A reference to a social media channel for a package.
entries.sourceArtifact: A reference to an artifact containing the sources for a package.
entries.staticAnalysisReport: A reference to a static analysis report for a package.
entries.support: A reference to the software support channel or other support information for a package.
entries.vcs: A reference to a version control system related to a software artifact.
entries.vulnerabilityDisclosureReport: A reference to a Vulnerability Disclosure Report (VDR) which provides the software supplier's analysis and findings describing the impact (or lack of impact) that reported vulnerabilities have on packages or products in the supplier's SBOM as defined in [NIST SP 800-161 Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management Practices for Systems and Organizations](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/161/r1/final).
entries.vulnerabilityExploitabilityAssessment: A reference to a Vulnerability Exploitability eXchange (VEX) statement which provides information on whether a product is impacted by a specific vulnerability in an included package and, if affected, whether there are actions recommended to remediate. See also [NTIA VEX one-page summary](https://ntia.gov/files/ntia/publications/vex_one-page_summary.pdf).

/Core/HashAlgorithm.name: HashAlgorithm
/Core/HashAlgorithm.summary: A mathematical algorithm that maps data of arbitrary size to a bit string.
/Core/HashAlgorithm.description:
A HashAlgorithm is a mathematical algorithm that maps data of arbitrary size to
a bit string (the hash) and is a one-way function, that is, a function which is
practically infeasible to invert.

entries.adler32: Adler-32 checksum is part of the widely used zlib compression library as defined in [RFC 1950](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc1950) Section 2.3.
entries.blake2b256: BLAKE2b algorithm with a digest size of 256, as defined in [RFC 7693](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc7693) Section 4.
entries.blake2b384: BLAKE2b algorithm with a digest size of 384, as defined in [RFC 7693](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc7693) Section 4.
entries.blake2b512: BLAKE2b algorithm with a digest size of 512, as defined in [RFC 7693](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc7693) Section 4.
entries.md2: MD2 message-digest algorithm, as defined in [RFC 1319](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc1319/).
entries.md4: MD4 message-digest algorithm, as defined in [RFC 1186](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc1186).
entries.md5: MD5 message-digest algorithm, as defined in [RFC 1321](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc1321).
entries.other: any hashing algorithm that does not exist in this list of entries
entries.sha1: SHA-1, a secure hashing algorithm, as defined in [RFC 3174](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc3174).
entries.sha224: SHA-2 with a digest length of 224, as defined in [RFC 3874](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc3874).
entries.sha256: SHA-2 with a digest length of 256, as defined in [RFC 6234](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc6234).
entries.sha384: SHA-2 with a digest length of 384, as defined in [RFC 6234](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc6234).
entries.sha512: SHA-2 with a digest length of 512, as defined in [RFC 6234](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc6234).
entries.sha3_224: SHA-3 with a digest length of 224, as defined in [FIPS 202](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/fips/202/final).
entries.sha3_256: SHA-3 with a digest length of 256, as defined in [FIPS 202](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/fips/202/final).
entries.sha3_384: SHA-3 with a digest length of 384, as defined in [FIPS 202](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/fips/202/final).
entries.sha3_512: SHA-3 with a digest length of 512, as defined in [FIPS 202](https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/fips/202/final).

/Core/SupportType.name: SupportType
/Core/SupportType.summary: Indicates the type of support that is associated with an artifact.
/Core/SupportType.description: SupportType is an enumeration of the various types of support commonly found for artifacts in the software supply chain. Specific details of what that support entails are provided by agreements between the producer and consumer of the artifact.

entries.development: the artifact is in active development and is not considered ready for formal support from the supplier.
entries.support: the artifact has been released, and is supported from the supplier.   There is a validUntilDate that can provide additional information about the duration of support.
entries.deployed: in addition to being supported by the supplier, the software is known to have been deployed and is in use.  For a software as a service provider, this implies the software is now available as a service.
entries.limitedSupport: the artifact has been released, and there is limited support available from the supplier. There is a validUntilDate that can provide additional information about the duration of support.
entries.endOfSupport: there is a defined end of support for the artifact from the supplier.  This may also be referred to as end of life. There is a validUntilDate that can be used to signal when support ends for the artifact.
entries.noSupport: there is no support for the artifact from the supplier, consumer assumes any support obligations.
entries.noAssertion: no assertion about the type of support is made.   This is considered the default if no other support type is used.

/Core/AnnotationType.name: AnnotationType
/Core/AnnotationType.summary: Specifies the type of an annotation.
/Core/AnnotationType.description: AnnotationType specifies the type of an annotation.

entries.other: Used to store extra information about an Element which is not part of a Review (e.g. extra information provided during the creation of the Element).
entries.review: Used when someone reviews the Element.

/Core/ExternalIdentifierType.name: ExternalIdentifierType
/Core/ExternalIdentifierType.summary: Specifies the type of an external identifier.
/Core/ExternalIdentifierType.description: ExteralIdentifierType specifies the type of an external identifier.

entries.cve: Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifiers, an identifier for a specific software flaw defined within the official CVE Dictionary and that conforms to the [CVE specification](https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/cve_id).
entries.email: Email address, as defined in [RFC 3696](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc3986) Section 3.
entries.gitoid: [Gitoid](https://www.iana.org/assignments/uri-schemes/prov/gitoid), stands for [Git Object ID](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Internals-Git-Objects). A gitoid of type blob is a unique hash of a binary artifact. A gitoid may represent either an [Artifact Identifier](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/eb1ee5c961c16215eb8709b2975d193a2007a35d/spec/SPEC.md#artifact-identifier-types) for the software artifact or an [Input Manifest Identifier](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/eb1ee5c961c16215eb8709b2975d193a2007a35d/spec/SPEC.md#input-manifest-identifier) for the software artifact's associated [Artifact Input Manifest](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/eb1ee5c961c16215eb8709b2975d193a2007a35d/spec/SPEC.md#artifact-input-manifest); this ambiguity exists because the Artifact Input Manifest is itself an artifact, and the gitoid of that artifact is its valid identifier. Gitoids calculated on software artifacts (Snippet, File, or Package Elements) should be recorded in the SPDX 3.0 SoftwareArtifact's contentIdentifier property. Gitoids calculated on the Artifact Input Manifest (Input Manifest Identifier) should be recorded in the SPDX 3.0 Element's externalIdentifier property. See [OmniBOR Specification](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/), a minimalistic specification for describing software [Artifact Dependency Graphs](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/eb1ee5c961c16215eb8709b2975d193a2007a35d/spec/SPEC.md#artifact-dependency-graph-adg).
entries.other: Used when the type does not match any of the other options.
entries.packageUrl: Package URL, as defined in the corresponding [Annex](../../../annexes/pkg-url-specification.md) of this specification.
entries.securityOther: Used when there is a security related identifier of unspecified type.
entries.swhid: SoftWare Hash IDentifier, a persistent intrinsic identifier for digital artifacts, such as files, trees (also known as directories or folders), commits, and other objects typically found in version control systems. The format of the identifiers is defined in the [SWHID specification](https://www.swhid.org/specification/v1.1/4.Syntax) (ISO/IEC DIS 18670). They typically look like `swh:1:cnt:94a9ed024d3859793618152ea559a168bbcbb5e2`.
entries.swid: Concise Software Identification (CoSWID) tag, as defined in [RFC 9393](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc9393) Section 2.3.
entries.urlScheme: [Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) Schemes](https://www.iana.org/assignments/uri-schemes/uri-schemes.xhtml). The scheme used in order to locate a resource.

/Core/RelationshipCompleteness.name: RelationshipCompleteness
/Core/RelationshipCompleteness.summary: Indicates whether a relationship is known to be complete, incomplete, or if no assertion is made with respect to relationship completeness.
/Core/RelationshipCompleteness.description: RelationshipCompleteness indicates whether the provided relationship is known to be complete, known to be incomplete, or if no assertion is made by the relationship creator.

entries.incomplete: The relationship is known not to be exhaustive.
entries.complete: The relationship is known to be exhaustive.
entries.noAssertion: No assertion can be made about the completeness of the relationship.

/Core/LifecycleScopeType.name: LifecycleScopeType
/Core/LifecycleScopeType.summary: Provide an enumerated set of lifecycle phases that can provide context to relationships.
/Core/LifecycleScopeType.description: This enumeration summarizes common phases when dependency and other relationships, have different implications, based on their context.  For example,  a build dependency, may have different implications than a operational dependency.

entries.design: A relationship has specific context implications during an element's design.
entries.development: A relationship has specific context implications during development phase of an element.
entries.build: A relationship has specific context implications during an element's build phase, during development.
entries.test: A relationship has specific context implications during an element's testing phase, during development.
entries.runtime: A relationship has specific context implications during the execution phase of an element.
entries.other: A relationship has other specific context information necessary to capture that the above set of enumerations does not handle.

/Core/NoAssertionElement.name: NoAssertionElement
/Core/NoAssertionElement.summary:
An Individual Value for Element representing a set of Elements of unknown
identify or cardinality (number).
/Core/NoAssertionElement.description:
NoAssertionElement should be used if

- the SPDX creator has attempted to but cannot reach a reasonable objective
  determination;
- the SPDX creator has made no attempt to determine this field; or
- the SPDX creator has intentionally provided no information (no meaning should
  be implied by doing so).

For example, a Relationship with
`relationshipType`="ancestorOf",
`from`=Element1,
and
`to`=NoAssertionElement
is explicitly expressing that
no assertion is being made about any potential descendents of Element1.

/Core/NoneElement.name: NoneElement
/Core/NoneElement.summary:
An Individual Value for Element representing a set of Elements with
cardinality (number/count) of zero.
/Core/NoneElement.description:
NoneLicenseElement should be used if the SPDX creator desires to assert that
there are NO elements for the given context of use.

For example, a Relationship with
`relationshipType`="ancestorOf",
`from`=Element1,
and `to`=NoneElement
is explicitly expressing an assertion that
Element1 has no descendents.

/Core/SemVer.name: SemVer
/Core/SemVer.summary: A string constrained to the SemVer 2.0.0 specification.
/Core/SemVer.description:
A semantic version is a string that is following the specification of
[Semantic Versioning 2.0.0](https://semver.org/).

/Core/DateTime.name: DateTime
/Core/DateTime.summary: A string representing a specific date and time.
/Core/DateTime.description:
A DateTime is a string representation of a specific date and time.

It has resolution of seconds and is always expressed in UTC time zone.

The specific format is one of the most commonly used ISO-8601 formats.

/Core/MediaType.name: MediaType
/Core/MediaType.summary:
Standardized way of indicating the type of content of an Element or a Property.
A String constrained to the RFC 2046 specificiation.
/Core/MediaType.description:
A MediaType is a string constrained to the
[RFC 2046 MIME Part Two: Media Types](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc2046).
It provides a standardized way of indicating the type of content of an Element
or a Property.

**Examples**

- `application/java-archive`
- `application/vcard+json`
- `application/vnd.oasis.opendocument.text`
- `image/avif`
- `text/csv;charset=UTF-8`
- `text/javascript`
- `text/spdx`

A list of all possible media types is available at
[IANA Protocol Registries](https://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml).

namespaces.name: Core
namespaces.summary: The basis for all SPDX profiles.
namespaces.description:
The Core namespace defines foundational concepts serving as the basis for all
SPDX-3.0 profiles.

/ExpandedLicensing/LicenseAddition.name: LicenseAddition
/ExpandedLicensing/LicenseAddition.summary:
Abstract class for additional text intended to be added to a License, but
which is not itself a standalone License.
/ExpandedLicensing/LicenseAddition.description:
A LicenseAddition represents text which is intended to be added to a License
as additional text, but which is not itself intended to be a standalone
License.

It may be an exception which is listed on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html)
(ListedLicenseException), or may be any other additional text (as an exception
or otherwise) which is defined by an SPDX data creator (CustomLicenseAddition).

/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicenseAddition.name: CustomLicenseAddition
/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicenseAddition.summary: A license addition that is not listed on the SPDX Exceptions List.
/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicenseAddition.description:
A CustomLicenseAddition represents an addition to a License that is not listed
on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html),
and is therefore defined by an SPDX data creator.

It is intended to represent additional language which is meant to be added to
a License, but which is not itself a standalone License.

/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicense.name: ListedLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicense.summary: A license that is listed on the SPDX License List.
/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicense.description:
A ListedLicense represents a License that is listed on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses).

/ExpandedLicensing/OrLaterOperator.name: OrLaterOperator
/ExpandedLicensing/OrLaterOperator.summary:
Portion of an AnyLicenseInfo representing this version, or any later version,
of the indicated License.
/ExpandedLicensing/OrLaterOperator.description:
An OrLaterOperator indicates that this portion of the AnyLicenseInfo
represents either (1) the specified version of the corresponding License, or
(2) any later version of that License. It is represented in the SPDX License
Expression Syntax by the `+` operator.

It is context-dependent, and unspecified by SPDX, as to what constitutes a
"later version" of any particular License. Some Licenses may not be versioned,
or may not have clearly-defined ordering for versions. The consumer of SPDX
data will need to determine for themselves what meaning to attribute to a
"later version" operator for a particular License.

/ExpandedLicensing/License.name: License
/ExpandedLicensing/License.summary: Abstract class for the portion of an AnyLicenseInfo representing a license.
/ExpandedLicensing/License.description:
A License represents a license text, whether listed on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses/)
(ListedLicense) or defined by an SPDX data creator (CustomLicense).

/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicense.name: CustomLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicense.summary: A license that is not listed on the SPDX License List.
/ExpandedLicensing/CustomLicense.description:
A CustomLicense represents a License that is not listed on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses),
and is therefore defined by an SPDX data creator.

/ExpandedLicensing/WithAdditionOperator.name: WithAdditionOperator
/ExpandedLicensing/WithAdditionOperator.summary:
Portion of an AnyLicenseInfo representing a License which has additional
text applied to it.
/ExpandedLicensing/WithAdditionOperator.description:
A WithAdditionOperator indicates that the designated License is subject to the
designated LicenseAddition, which might be a license exception on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html)
(ListedLicenseException) or may be other additional text
(CustomLicenseAddition). It is represented in the SPDX License Expression
Syntax by the `WITH` operator.

/ExpandedLicensing/IndividualLicensingIn.name: IndividualLicensingInfo
/ExpandedLicensing/IndividualLicensingIn.summary:
A concrete subclass of AnyLicenseInfo used by Individuals in the
ExpandedLicensing profile.
/ExpandedLicensing/IndividualLicensingIn.description:
Individuals, such as NoneLicense and NoAssertionLicense, need to reference a
concrete subclass of AnyLicenseInfo.

This class provides the type used by the individuals.

/ExpandedLicensing/DisjunctiveLicenseSet.name: DisjunctiveLicenseSet
/ExpandedLicensing/DisjunctiveLicenseSet.summary:
Portion of an AnyLicenseInfo representing a set of licensing information where
only one of the elements applies.
/ExpandedLicensing/DisjunctiveLicenseSet.description:
A DisjunctiveLicenseSet indicates that _only one_ of its subsidiary
AnyLicenseInfos is required to apply. In other words, a DisjunctiveLicenseSet
of two or more licenses represents a licensing situation where _only one_ of
the specified licenses are to be complied with.

A consumer of SPDX data would typically understand this to permit the recipient
of the licensed content to choose which of the corresponding license they would
prefer to use. It is represented in the SPDX License Expression Syntax by the
`OR` operator.

/ExpandedLicensing/ExtendableLicense.name: ExtendableLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/ExtendableLicense.summary: Abstract class representing a License or an OrLaterOperator.
/ExpandedLicensing/ExtendableLicense.description:
The WithAdditionOperator can have a License or an OrLaterOperator as the
license property value. This class is used for the value.

/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicenseExceptio.name: ListedLicenseException
/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicenseExceptio.summary: A license exception that is listed on the SPDX Exceptions list.
/ExpandedLicensing/ListedLicenseExceptio.description:
A ListedLicenseException represents an exception to a License (in other words,
an exception to a license condition or an additional permission beyond those
granted in a License) which is listed on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html).

/ExpandedLicensing/ConjunctiveLicenseSet.name: ConjunctiveLicenseSet
/ExpandedLicensing/ConjunctiveLicenseSet.summary:
Portion of an AnyLicenseInfo representing a set of licensing information
where all elements apply.
/ExpandedLicensing/ConjunctiveLicenseSet.description:
A ConjunctiveLicenseSet indicates that _each_ of its subsidiary
AnyLicenseInfos apply. In other words, a ConjunctiveLicenseSet of two or
more licenses represents a licensing situation where _all_ of the specified
licenses are to be complied with. It is represented in the SPDX License
Expression Syntax by the `AND` operator.

It is syntactically correct to specify a ConjunctiveLicenseSet where the
subsidiary AnyLicenseInfos may be "incompatible" according to a particular
interpretation of the corresponding Licenses.
The
[SPDX License Expression Syntax](../../../annexes/spdx-license-expressions.md)
does not take into account interpretation of license texts, which is
left to the consumer of SPDX data to determine for themselves.

/ExpandedLicensing/isOsiApproved.name: isOsiApproved
/ExpandedLicensing/isOsiApproved.summary:
Specifies whether the License is listed as approved by the
Open Source Initiative (OSI).
/ExpandedLicensing/isOsiApproved.description:
isOsiApproved specifies whether the
[Open Source Initiative (OSI)](https://opensource.org)
has listed this License as "approved" in their list of OSI Approved Licenses,
located at the time of this writing at
[OSI Approved Licenses](https://opensource.org/licenses).

A value of "true" indicates that the license is in the list of licenses that
OSI publishes as approved.

A value of "false" indicates that the license is explicitly not in the
corresponding list of OSI licenses (e.g., OSI has stated publicly that a
license is not approved).

If the isOsiApproved field is not specified, the SPDX data creator makes no
assertions about whether the License is approved by the OSI.

/ExpandedLicensing/licenseXml.name: licenseXml
/ExpandedLicensing/licenseXml.summary:
Identifies all the text and metadata associated with a license in the license
XML format.
/ExpandedLicensing/licenseXml.description:
The license XML format is defined and used by the SPDX legal team.

The formal schema definition is available at
[SPDX License List XML Schema](https://github.com/spdx/license-list-XML/blob/v3.25.0/schema/ListedLicense.xsd).

For a text description of the XML fields, see
[XML template fields](https://github.com/spdx/license-list-XML/blob/v3.25.0/DOCS/xml-fields.md).

/ExpandedLicensing/seeAlso.name: seeAlso
/ExpandedLicensing/seeAlso.summary: Contains a URL where the License or LicenseAddition can be found in use.
/ExpandedLicensing/seeAlso.description:
A seeAlso defines a cross-reference with a URL where the License or
LicenseAddition can be found in use by one or a few projects.

If applicable, it should include a URL where the license text is posted by
the license steward, particularly if the license steward has made available a
"canonical" primary URL for the license text.

If the license is OSI approved, a seeAlso should be included with the URL for
the license's listing on the OSI website.

The seeAlso URL may refer to a previously-available URL for the License or
LicenseAddition which is no longer active.

Where applicable, the seeAlso URL should include the license text in its
native language. seeAlso URLs to English or other translations may be included
where multiple, equivalent official translations exist.

/ExpandedLicensing/additionText.name: additionText
/ExpandedLicensing/additionText.summary: Identifies the full text of a LicenseAddition.
/ExpandedLicensing/additionText.description:
An additionText contains the plain text of the LicenseAddition, without
templating or other similar markup.

Users of the additionText for a License can apply the
[SPDX License List Matching Guidelines](../../../annexes/license-matching-guidelines-and-templates.md)
when comparing it to another text for matching purposes.

/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedLicenseId.name: isDeprecatedLicenseId
/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedLicenseId.summary:
Specifies whether a license or additional text identifier has been marked as
deprecated.
/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedLicenseId.description:
The isDeprecatedLicenseId property specifies whether an identifier for a
License or LicenseAddition has been marked as deprecated. If the property
is not defined, then it is presumed to be false (i.e., not deprecated).

If the License or LicenseAddition is included on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses/), then
the `deprecatedVersion` property indicates on which version release of the
License List it was first marked as deprecated.

"Deprecated" in this context refers to deprecating the use of the
_identifier_, not the underlying license. In other words, even if a License's
author or steward has stated that a particular License generally should not be
used, that would _not_ mean that the License's identifier is "deprecated."
Rather, a License or LicenseAddition operator is typically marked as
"deprecated" when it is determined that use of another identifier is
preferable.

/ExpandedLicensing/member.name: member
/ExpandedLicensing/member.summary: A license expression participating in a license set.
/ExpandedLicensing/member.description:
A member is a license expression participating in a conjunctive (of type
ConjunctiveLicenseSet) or a disjunctive (of type DisjunctiveLicenseSet)
license set.

/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedAdditionI.name: isDeprecatedAdditionId
/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedAdditionI.summary: Specifies whether an additional text identifier has been marked as deprecated.
/ExpandedLicensing/isDeprecatedAdditionI.description:
The isDeprecatedAdditionId property specifies whether an identifier for a
LicenseAddition has been marked as deprecated. If the property is not defined,
then it is presumed to be false (i.e., not deprecated).

If the LicenseAddition is included on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html),
then the `deprecatedVersion` property indicates on which version release of the
Exceptions List it was first marked as deprecated.

"Deprecated" in this context refers to deprecating the use of the
_identifier_, not the underlying license addition. In other words, even if a
LicenseAddition's author or steward has stated that a particular
LicenseAddition generally should not be used, that would _not_ mean that the
LicenseAddition's identifier is "deprecated." Rather, a LicenseAddition
operator is typically marked as "deprecated" when it is determined that use of
another identifier is preferable.

/ExpandedLicensing/listVersionAdded.name: listVersionAdded
/ExpandedLicensing/listVersionAdded.summary:
Specifies the SPDX License List version in which this ListedLicense or
ListedLicenseException identifier was first added.
/ExpandedLicensing/listVersionAdded.description:
A listVersionAdded for a ListedLicense or ListedLicenseException on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses/)
specifies which version release of the License List was the first
one in which it was included.

/ExpandedLicensing/obsoletedBy.name: obsoletedBy
/ExpandedLicensing/obsoletedBy.summary:
Specifies the licenseId that is preferred to be used in place of a deprecated
License or LicenseAddition.
/ExpandedLicensing/obsoletedBy.description:
An obsoletedBy value for a deprecated License or LicenseAddition specifies
the licenseId of the replacement License or LicenseAddition that is preferred
to be used in its place. It should use the same format as specified for a
licenseId.

The License's or LicenseAddition's comment value may include more information
about the reason why the licenseId specified in the obsoletedBy value is
preferred.

/ExpandedLicensing/subjectLicense.name: subjectLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectLicense.summary: A License participating in an 'or later' model.
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectLicense.description:
A subjectLicense is a License which is subject an 'or later' effect
(OrLaterOperator).

/ExpandedLicensing/subjectAddition.name: subjectAddition
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectAddition.summary: A LicenseAddition participating in a 'with addition' model.
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectAddition.description:
A subjectAddition is a LicenseAddition which is subject to a 'with additional
text' effect (WithAdditionOperator).

/ExpandedLicensing/deprecatedVersion.name: deprecatedVersion
/ExpandedLicensing/deprecatedVersion.summary:
Specifies the SPDX License List version in which this license or exception
identifier was deprecated.
/ExpandedLicensing/deprecatedVersion.description:
A deprecatedVersion, for a ListedLicense on the
[SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses/)
or a ListedLicenseException on the
[SPDX License Exceptions](https://spdx.org/licenses/exceptions-index.html),
specifies which version release of the License List was the first
one in which it was marked as deprecated.

/ExpandedLicensing/isFsfLibre.name: isFsfLibre
/ExpandedLicensing/isFsfLibre.summary:
Specifies whether the License is listed as free by the
Free Software Foundation (FSF).
/ExpandedLicensing/isFsfLibre.description:
isFsfLibre specifies whether the
[Free Software Foundation (FSF)](https://fsf.org)
has listed this License as "free" in their commentary on licenses, located at
the time of this writing at
[Various Licenses and Comments about Them](https://www.gnu.org/licenses/license-list.en.html).

A value of "true" indicates that the license is in the list of licenses that
FSF publishes as libre.

A value of "false" indicates that the license is explicitly not in the
corresponding list of FSF libre licenses (e.g., FSF has the license on a
non-free list).

If the isFsfLibre field is not specified, the SPDX data creator makes no
assertions about whether the License is listed in the FSF's commentary.

/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseHeader.name: standardLicenseHeader
/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseHeader.summary:
Provides a License author's preferred text to indicate that a file is covered
by the License.
/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseHeader.description:
A standardLicenseHeader contains the plain text of the License author's
preferred wording to be used, typically in a source code file's header
comments or similar location, to indicate that the file is subject to
the specified License.

/ExpandedLicensing/subjectExtendableLice.name: subjectExtendableLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectExtendableLice.summary: A License participating in a 'with addition' model.
/ExpandedLicensing/subjectExtendableLice.description:
A subjectExtendableLicense is a License which is subject to a 'with additional
text' effect (WithAdditionOperator).

/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseTempla.name: standardLicenseTemplate
/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseTempla.summary: Identifies the full text of a License, in SPDX templating format.
/ExpandedLicensing/standardLicenseTempla.description:
A standardLicenseTemplate contains a license template which describes sections
of the License text which can be varied.

See the Legacy Text Template format section of the
[SPDX License List Matching Guidelines](../../../annexes/license-matching-guidelines-and-templates.md)
for format information.

It is recommended to use [licenseXml](./licenseXml.md) instead, as it can
capture all the text and metadata associated with a license.

/ExpandedLicensing/standardAdditionTempl.name: standardAdditionTemplate
/ExpandedLicensing/standardAdditionTempl.summary: Identifies the full text of a LicenseAddition, in SPDX templating format.
/ExpandedLicensing/standardAdditionTempl.description:
A standardAdditionTemplate contains a license addition template which describes
sections of the LicenseAddition text which can be varied.

See the Legacy Text Template format section of the
[SPDX License List Matching Guidelines](../../../annexes/license-matching-guidelines-and-templates.md)
for format information.

It is recommended to use [licenseXml](./licenseXml.md) instead, as it can
capture all the text and metadata associated with a license.

/ExpandedLicensing/NoAssertionLicense.name: NoAssertionLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/NoAssertionLicense.summary:
An Individual Value for License when no assertion can be made about its actual
value.
/ExpandedLicensing/NoAssertionLicense.description:
NoAssertionLicense should be used if

- the SPDX creator has attempted to but cannot reach a reasonable objective
  determination;
- the SPDX creator has made no attempt to determine this field; or
- the SPDX creator has intentionally provided no information (no meaning should
  be implied by doing so).

/ExpandedLicensing/NoneLicense.name: NoneLicense
/ExpandedLicensing/NoneLicense.summary:
An Individual Value for License where the SPDX data creator determines that no
license is present.
/ExpandedLicensing/NoneLicense.description:
NoneLicense should be used if the SPDX creator determines there is no license
available for this Artifact.

namespaces.name: ExpandedLicensing
namespaces.description:
This profile supports representing a fully expanded
[license expression](../../annexes/spdx-license-expressions.md)
in object form.
